ravelogues, personal letters, diaries, photos, and interviews, Minawi shows how the loyalties of these imperialists were questioned and their ethnic identification weaponized. As the once diverse empire comes to an end, they are forced to give up their home in the imperial capital. An alternative history of the last four decades of the Ottoman Empire, Losing Istanbul frames global pivotal events through the experiences of Arab-Ottoman imperial loyalists who called Istanbul home, on the eve of a vanishing imperial world order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArabszTurkeyzIstanbulxHistory. 0aEthnicityzTurkeyzIstanbulxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aAbdulhamid.  aAfrica.  aArabs.  aBalkans.  aEnd of Empire.  aImperialists.  aMicro-History.  aOttoman Empire.  aRace.  aTurkey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363405340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503634053423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503634053/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles